        "text": "Remarks: The first two solutions apply directly over any field of characteristic zero. (The result fails in characteristic p > 0 because we may take P = (x + … · + x2) = x + …  + x .) he hird solution can be extended to complex coefficients by replacing P(∇) by its complex conjugate, and again the result may be deduced for any field of characteristic zero. Stanley also suggests Section 5 of the arXiv e-print math . C0/0502363 for some algebraic background for this problem.",
